WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.360 --> 00:00:02.860
While quantum computers won't be suited to solve

2
00:00:02.860 --> 00:00:05.740
all problems there are a few problem classes

3
00:00:05.740 --> 00:00:08.360
and potential use cases where we expect

4
00:00:08.360 --> 00:00:11.040
quantum computing to have an impact.

5
00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:13.340
Those include simulation such

6
00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:15.880
as modeling processes and systems that occur in

7
00:00:15.880 --> 00:00:18.360
nature, search an optimization

8
00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:20.559
involving searching for the best or

9
00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:22.720
optimal solution in a situation with

10
00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:25.700
many possible answers, and mathematics

11
00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:28.520
and processing data with complex structure

12
00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:31.740
including applications for machine learning.

13
00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:34.700
Quantum algorithms take a new approach to

14
00:00:34.700 --> 00:00:37.180
these sorts of problems, leveraging

15
00:00:37.180 --> 00:00:39.680
the unique features of quantum physics like

16
00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:42.640
superposition, interference, and entanglement.

17
00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:44.380
Regular computers get stuck

18
00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:46.840
exploring certain areas of the computational space

19
00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:49.620
so they can not find these patterns.

20
00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:51.760
Quantum computers are equipped with

21
00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:54.940
extra capabilities or increased performance

22
00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:59.160
for some problems afforded by their quantum nature.

23
00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:02.119
To fully understand the potential of quantum computers

24
00:01:02.120 --> 00:01:06.460
it requires a deep dive into computational complexity theory,

25
00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:09.220
a branch of computer science that centers on

26
00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:13.200
measuring and comparing the computational effort that

27
00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:16.640
goes into solving different kinds of problems.

28
00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:18.880
This provides a useful framework

29
00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:21.080
for describing various speed-ups

30
00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:23.999
and problem classes that are encountered in

31
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:24.520
computing.
